Diatoms are eukaryotic unicellular algae that account for about 40% of the oceans primary productivity and produce intricately nanopatterned cells wall made out of silica (see figure 1). The biological formation of inorganic materials with complex form (biominerals) is a widespread phenomenon in nature that occurs in almost all taxonomic groups from prokaryotes (e.g. Fe3O4 nanocrystals in magnetotactic bacteria) to humans (bones and teeth), yet the molecular mechanisms underlying biomineral morphogenesis are not well understood. The formation of the diatom biosilica is an extremely rapid process that is accomplished under mild physiological conditions, thus exceeding the capabilities of present-day materials engineering. 
In search of the biological molecules that control biosilica morphogenesis, biochemical analysis of the diatom biosilica-associated organic components led to the discovery of novel biomolecules termed silaffins and long-chain polyamines (LCPA). Silaffins and LCPAs are able to drastically influence silica formation but are not able to replicate a diatom cell wall structure in vitro indicating that additional components are required for formation of the nanopatterned cell wall structures. Recently, diatom genome sequencing projects have provided the opportunity to identify the entire set of proteins involved in silica formation. However, subsequent transcriptomics and proteomics analyses that identified hundreds of potential candidate proteins failed to identify already known silica forming proteins, which raises concerns regarding the specificity and suitability of such high-throughput methods for studying diatom silica formation. 
One of the goals of this project was to develop novel bioinformatics methods that would allow for the identification of additional components of the cell wall formation machinery. Searching for proteins containing domains that mimic the amino acid compositions (rather than sequence) of known silica forming proteins, silaffins retrieved the known silaffin proteins in addition to 86 other proteins. Among these silaffin-like proteins are six proteins, which we denoted cingulins, that exhibit unique and highly repetitive amino acid sequence motifs. Subsequent analysis of the intracellular location of cingulins revealed that they are integral components of a silica-forming organic matrix (microrings) (see figure 2). The cingulin-containing microrings are specifically ...
